The article discusses the establishment of the fight against global corruption as a core national security interest by President Joseph R. Biden Jr. through National Security Study Memorandum 1 (NSSM-1) on June 3, 2021. The article mentions that corruption threatens United States national security, economic equity, global anti-poverty and development efforts, and democracy itself. The administration issued the first United States Strategy on Countering Corruption on December 6, 2021, which aims to prevent and combat corruption, deepen global partnerships, and eliminate safe havens for corrupt actors and their criminal proceeds. The article highlights the role of enablers of corruption, who often operate through opaque legal structures and financial mechanisms, and emphasizes the need to use legal, policy, diplomatic, economic, and financial tools to deter corruption. The proclamation issued by President Biden suspends the entry into the United States of individuals involved in significant corruption and their immediate family members, with the identification of covered individuals to be determined by the Secretary of State. The implementation of the proclamation will be carried out by the Secretary of State and the Secretary of Homeland Security. The proclamation includes exceptions for lawful permanent residents, individuals granted asylum, refugees, and those whose entry would further important United States law enforcement objectives. The proclamation remains in effect until terminated by the President. The article concludes with general provisions and clarifies that the proclamation does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or its entities.